{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"577668b5-5e48-4fea-ab6b-9ea36d92ab53","content":"## What happened\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, **overload resolution changed** for extension methods on arrays. When you call `array.Contains(num)` on an `int[]`, the compiler now prefers:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)\n```\n\nover the old:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)\n```\n\nbecause `T[]` is implicitly convertible to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, and C# 14 considers span-based extensions as better matches. Since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, it cannot be represented in expression trees — causing the failure.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler picks the `Enumerable` overload. Two options:\n\n**Option A — Cast to `IEnumerable<int>`:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B — Call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nEither approach forces the compiler to bind to the `IEnumerable<T>`-based overload, which expression trees can represent. The same issue affects other methods that exist on both `Enumerable` and `MemoryExtensions` (e.g., `SequenceEqual`), so watch for those too.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a66c40a8-8983-4134-8669-4c69b7dc7918","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when using `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14, there's a significant change related to extension methods. C# 14 introduces a new \"extension\" feature (extension types/blocks). But more relevantly, there's been a change in how the compiler resolves `Contains` on arrays.\n\nActually, let me