terpreter has different limitations than the IL-emitting compiler, so a subtle change in method resolution could cause a runtime exception when `preferInterpretation: true` is set.\n\nThe most likely culprit is that C# 14 now resolves `array.Contains(num)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<int>(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains`, but since expression trees can't use `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, the compiler either throws a compile-time error or falls back to `Enumerable.Contains`. If the user is seeing a runtime exception, they might be mistaken about when the error occurs, or there's something else going on with how the expression tree is being evaluated.\n\nWait, let me reconsider—what if `System.Array` itself gained a `Contains` instance method in .NET 10? That would cause the compiler to prefer the instance method over the extension method, which could change the behavior entirely.\n\nActually, thinking about this differently: in C# 14, `array.Contains(x)` in regular code probably resolves to a span-based extension method, but expression trees can't handle spans. So the compiler should throw a compile-time error about ref structs or optional parameters in expression trees. Either the user is misreporting this as a runtime error, or there's something else going on that I'm missing about how the compiler handles this fallback. the expression tree is actually compiled or executed. So it could be either depending on when the check happens.\n\nGiven the user's phrasing \"runtime error,\" I'm leaning toward this being a runtime failure—the compiler allows it through, but when the expression tree tries to compile or execute, it hits the span limitation. The solutions would be to explicitly use `Enumerable.Contains` or cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the older overload resolution. Actually, I think the real issue here is a breaking change in .NET 10's overload resolution. The C# 14 compiler now treats `ReadOnlySpan<T>` extensions as better matches for arrays since `T[]` implicitly converts to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, which affects methods like `Contains` and `SequenceEqual` that exist on both array and span types.\n\nFor expression trees, this would normally be a compile-time error since you can't represent span-based methods in an expression tree. But if the user is manually constructing the expression tree using `Expression.Call` elsewhere in their code, they might be able to build it without the compiler catching it, only to hit a runtime error when the expression tree tries to execute a method that can't be represented.\n\nThe real issue is that C# 14 changed overload resolution so `array.Contains(value)` now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Since ref structs can't exist in expression trees, this breaks the code. The fix is to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains(array, num)` to force the older overload. The compiler would actually reject this at compile time with an error about expression trees not supporting ref structs like `ReadOnlySpan<int>`, since the `Contains` method gets resolved to the `MemoryExtensions` overload that requires a span conversion. So this is a compile-time error rather than a runtime one, and I should clarify that in my answer along with the fixes. The `preferInterpretation: true` flag is key here—the expression tree interpreter has known limitations that differ from compiled IL. Even if the compiler generates valid expression trees, the interpreter might struggle with subtle structural changes in .NET 10, like different conversion nodes from altered extension method resolution ordering. So the answer is C.\n\nActually, .NET 14 changed overload resolution to prefer `MemoryExtensions.Contains` (the span-based version) over `Enumerable.Contains` for arrays. In expression trees, this either fails at compile time with an error about ref structs not being allowed, or if the tree is built dynamically, fails at runtim